\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of the transfer operator was introduced by David Ruelle
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ruelle1986"

\end_inset

[verify ref] as a powerful mechanism for studying the nature of iterated
 maps.
 Before this, iterated functions were typically studied by looking at the
 trajectories of sets of points.
 This approach, though obvious, has disadvantages for both the disciplines
 of physics (
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 loss of differentiability) and mathematics (
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 non-measurable sets, axiom of choice).
 The transfer operator, sometimes called the Perron-Frobenius operator,
 or the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator, provides a different, stronger
 setting, by making incorporating the topology of the space that the map
 acts on.
 This section provides a gentle introduction to the concept.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, an iterated function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:X\to X$
\end_inset

 maps a space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to itself.
 When studying an iterated function, one often asks about the orbits of
 points: Are there fixed points, attractors or repellors, or saddle points?
 Is the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 may be ergodic or chaotic? Endowing the set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with a topology (for the unit interval, the natural topology on the reals),
 one typically asks if 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is strong or weak mixing, or merely topologically mixing.
 The above questions may all be grouped under a heading: 'the study of iterated
 operators by means of point set topology'.
 A change in perspective is gained by introducing a measure on the space
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This radically alters how 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be discussed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider how 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 acts on distributions, rather than points.
 Suppose the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, consider a dusting of points on the unit interval, with a
 local density given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and then consider how this dusting or density evolves upon iteration by
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 This verbal description may be given form as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho^{\prime}(y)=\int_{0}^{1}\,\delta\left(y-g(x)\right)\rho(x)\; dx\label{eq:transfer-dirac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}(y)$
\end_inset

 is the new density at point 
\begin_inset Formula $y=g(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the Dirac delta function.
 In this viewpoint, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 becomes an operator that maps densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 to other densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, or notationally, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho=\rho^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset

The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is called the transfer operator or the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator.
 It is a linear operator, for clearly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{g}(a\rho_{1}+b\rho_{2})=a\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho_{1}+b\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho_{2}
\]

\end_inset

for constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 and densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

density
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map from the unit interval to the non-negative reals, there
 is no particular need to enforce this.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 may be a map from the unit interval to any ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and it need not be smooth, differentiable or even continuous.
 Usually, we'll take the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to the reals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, but in fact, it could be any ring or field.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is an operator that maps functions on the unit interval to other functions
 on the unit interval: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{g}:\mathcal{F}\left[0,1\right]\to\mathcal{F}\left[0,1\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\in\mathcal{F}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The precise properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 depend strongly on what, exactly, is taken to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the set of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 on the unit interval
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 An exploration of the different spaces makes up much of the content of
 this paper.
 There are many spaces to choose from: the space of polynomials, the space
 of square-integrable functions, or possibly yet other spaces.
 In general, the properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 depend on the topology given to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Most generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is an operator acting on a topological space endowed with multiplication
 and addition, that is, a topological vector space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transfer-dirac"

\end_inset

, for a general space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, requires the definition of an integral on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and the definition of the Dirac delta function.
 This is in general possible only when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is endowed with a measure and the associated Borel sigma algebra.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 then must be a space of of measurable, sigma-additive functions, if eqn
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transfer-dirac"

\end_inset

 is to be meaningful.
 Given this setting, the transfer operator turns out to be one and the same
 as the push-forward of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 on the set of measurable, sigma-additive functions.
 A formalization and proof of this is given in a much later section.
 For most of what follows, though, these formalities can be avoided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is differentiable, and doesn't have a vanishing derivative, the transfer
 operator can be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{g}\rho\right]\left(y\right)=\sum_{x:y=g(x)}\frac{\rho(x)}{\left|dg(x)/dx\right|}\label{eq: transfer-jacobi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum is presumed to extend over at most a countable number of points.
 It is not at all hard to show that, for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reasonable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 class of differentiable functions, that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transfer-dirac"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: transfer-jacobi"

\end_inset

 are equivalent definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator, all of the usual language of operator theory may
 be brought to bear on its study.
 As a start, one looks for its representations and the eigenvectors and
 eigenspaces associated with each representation.
 It is typically pertinent to discuss any symmetries and isomorphisms these
 spaces might have.
 Thus, for example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is a compact operator, then it's spectrum is constrained by well-known
 theorems[need ref]: the spectrum is discrete, countable, bounded, and,
 if infinite, has an accumulation point at zero.
 It is from here whence the transfer operator gets the name 'Perron-Frobenius':
 insofar as compact operators are 'a lot like' finite matrices, the Perron-Frobe
nius theorem applies.
 So, for example, if one chooses the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 to be the space of polynomials on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, then, for many 'reasonable' 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 After we narrow the discussion to the Bernoulli operator, we will find
 that this is exactly the case.
 Alternately, one may choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 to be a Banach space, or possibly a Hilbert space of square-integrable
 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, it turns out that, for many 'reasonable' 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, that the conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is and isometry and specifically, a shift operator.
 In this case, it is well-known from the Wold-von Neumann decomposition
 that the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 fills the entire unit disk on the complex plane.
 We'll provide several constructions for the Bernoulli operator that exhibit
 this (and more; a spectrum that fills the entire complex plane!).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The composition operator 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{g}:\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]\to\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 acts on functions and is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{g}f=f\circ g$
\end_inset

.
 It is the right-inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 but usually not the left inverse: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{g}C_{g}$
\end_inset

 is the identity, but 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{g}\mathcal{L}_{g}$
\end_inset

 is not, in general.
 In physics, the composition operator is known as the Koopman operator
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Koopman1931"

\end_inset

.
 In mathematics, the AMS category 47B33 is used to classify articles pertaining
 to the study of composition operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both operators have physical significance, and occur frequently in the study
 of dynamical systems and statistical mechanics.
 For example, Ruelle has shown that the Fourrier transform of the correlation
 function for Axiom A dynamical systems is meromorphic on a strip
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ruelle1986-PRL"

\end_inset

; the poles of the correlation function are now called Ruelle reosnances,
 and can be shown to correspond to the logarithm of the eigenvalues of the
 transfer operator.
 In particular, this is where the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from: in spin-lattice systems, the transfer matrix simply describes
 how nearest-neighbor states are connected.
 When the interaction is long-range, the matrix becomes infinite-dimensional,
 and thus an operator.
 That it also typically happens to satisfy the provisions of the Frobenius-Perro
n theorem is where the name 'Frobenius-Perron operator comes from.
 Other physically significant constructions follow, including the resolvant,
 the Fredholm determinant and the dynamical zeta function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cantor set, and more generally, the product topology on infinite Cartesian
 products, plays a special role in what follows.
 This is in part due to the nature of shift operators and the Wold decomposition
, but can be considered a generalization.
 To keep things simple, consider the unit interval.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, one may write the decimal expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.d_{1}d_{2}d_{3}\cdots=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}d_{n}10^{-n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th decimal digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The space of all such decimal expansions is the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $D\times D\times D\times\cdots$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\left\{ 0,1,2,3,\cdots,9\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Although this is 'obvious', it is not commonly appreciated that this infinite
 Cartesian product is the Cantor set.
 This has practical implications for the study of transfer operators: one
 may choose to work with not only the 'natural' topology on the unit interval,
 but also with the Cantor set topology (aka the product topology or 'cylinder
 set' topology).
 This can have a subtle effect on the space of measurable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

, and can, as well, open up new ways of thinking about the problem, thus
 offering additional tools, techniques and theorems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be more precise, one considers the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 to consist of the set of strings 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega=\left\{ \sigma=(\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\ldots)\,:\,\sigma_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1,\ldots,p-1\right\} \,,\, x=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\sigma_{k}p^{-(k+1)}\;,\, x\in[0,1]\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

Intuitively, this set is simply the set of all the digits of a base-
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 expansion of the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 That one may consider a shift operator on this space is now intuitively
 obvious; that this shift operator has anything at all to do with that of
 the Wold decomposition is less so.
 This connection will be explored in greater detail in this text.
 This space is equivalent to the collection of all field configurations
 of a one-dimensional, one-sided lattice, where each lattice location can
 take on one of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 values.
 In physics, such lattices are called 'spin lattices' or 'spin networks';
 this cross-over of concepts provides another way of gaining insight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few more remarks remain in order.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 may be endowed with one of two different metrics: the natural metric, the
 closure of which leads to the natural topology on the real numbers, and
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic metric, whose closure gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic numbers.
 These are important to the study of finite function fields and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic analysis in general.
 Although this can be quite interesting, this text does not currently deal
 any further with the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic metric or the resulting closure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The real numbers also have yet another product representation.
 By considering 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}\times\cdots$
\end_inset

, one has sequences of positive integers that may be interpreted as a continued
 fraction: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=[0;\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\sigma_{3},\ldots]=\frac{1}{\sigma_{1}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{2}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{3}+\ldots}}}
\]

\end_inset

The measure on this product space is radically different than the usual
 measure, and is considerably harder to study; it is the Minkowski measure,
 the derivative of the Minkowski question-mark function.
 An introduction to lattice models, the product topology, and their applications
 to the study of transfer operators for continued fractions may be found
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "May91"

\end_inset

.
 Another exploration with certain specific results can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

.
 The continued fraction will not be further addressed in this text; see
 instead 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-GKW"

\end_inset

 for a detailed treatment.
\end_layout

