\begin_layout Section
Lattice model topology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well-known that one-dimensional lattice models, and more generally,
 subshifts of finite type, can provide useful tools and insights for the
 study of one-dimensional iterated maps
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "May91"

\end_inset

.
 This section recaps the use of a one-dimensional spin lattice for the construct
ion of a class of Bernoulli operator eigenfunctions.
 In essence, the lattice models recapture the Wold decomposition of section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Wold-decomposition"

\end_inset

, but using a more articulated, richer vocabulary.
 In particular, the shift operator gets a more concrete interpretation as
 a translation on a lattice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a one-sided lattice of points, labeled by the positive integers,
 that is, by 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 At each lattice location, a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{n}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (a name deriving from physics), can take one of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 values, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{n}\in\left\{ 0,1,2,\cdots,p-1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The space of states of the lattice is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=p\times p\times\cdots=p^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 where we write 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv\left\{ 0,1,2,\cdots,p-1\right\} $
\end_inset

, letting the number stand for the set.
 A given lattice configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=(\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 can be taken to be either a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic number, or as a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, with the Cantor mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $x:\Omega\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

 from the set of all lattice configurations 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x(\sigma)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\sigma_{n}p^{-n}\label{eq:Cantor mapping}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This mapping allows every possible spin lattice configuration to be mapped
 into the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, although not vice-versa: the natural topology on the spin lattice is finer
 than the natural topology on the reals, in that, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=(0,1,1,\cdots)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0,0,\cdots)$
\end_inset

 are inequivalent lattice configurations, whereas the binary numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $0.0111\ldots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1000\ldots$
\end_inset

 both represent the rational 1/2.
 Only certain rationals are double-pointed like this, whereas all irrationals
 correspond to a unique lattice configuration.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

, the Stone representation theorem applies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any Cartesian product of spaces has a natural topology, called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

product topology
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; the basis of the topology are referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cylinder sets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kle08,May91"

\end_inset

.
 Since the one-dimensional lattice is the Cartesian product of an infinite
 number of finite sets, the product topology applies.
 In fact, the product topology will prove very nice to work with; it is
 a reasonably coarse topology, yet, it is compatible with the natural topology
 on the reals.
 One particularly strong utility of the product topology is that it enables
 the definition and discussion of measurable (integrable) functions that
 are discontinuous at all rational numbers; by contrast, such constructions
 are extremely awkward when using Fourier series, and, of course, impossible
 in the language of analysis.
 We'll construct many such functions here; in what follows, the product
 topology will be made great use of.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The product topology allows a set of fractal eigenfunctions to be constructed
 for the Bernoulli operator.
 One begins by noting that the left-shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 on the lattice, defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau(\sigma)=\tau((\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots))=(\sigma_{2},\sigma_{3},\cdots)
\]

\end_inset

corresponds exactly to the Bernoulli map: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(\tau(\sigma))=2x(\sigma)-\left\lfloor 2x(\sigma)\right\rfloor 
\]

\end_inset

where we've written 
\begin_inset Formula $x(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to help remind that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should be thought of as a map, not a real number.
 For the remainder of this section, this distinction will rarely be made
 again, although every occurrence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{x}$
\end_inset

 should be implicitly understood to be the map 
\begin_inset Formula $x:\Omega\to[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now some arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\Omega\to F$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 may be taken to be the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, or some arbitrary general field.
 Then, given some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in F$
\end_inset

, one may construct the sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H(\sigma)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}V(\tau^{n}\sigma)\label{eq:Lattice Hamlitonian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{n}\sigma=(\tau\circ\tau\circ\cdots\circ\tau)(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 is simply the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold iteration of the shift operator.
 In physics, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is usually called the translation-invariant Hamiltonian for the system,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the interaction potential.
 For a one-sided lattice, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not strictly translation invariant, as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H(\tau(\sigma))=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}V(\tau^{n+1}\sigma)=\frac{H(\sigma)-V(\sigma)}{\lambda}\label{eq:Hamiltonian left shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Almost, because the one-sided lattice introduces a correction 
\begin_inset Formula $V/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For the bi-infinite, two-sided lattice, a truly translation-invariant Hamiltoni
an can be defined.
 The two-sided lattice model corresponds to the Bakers map, and is treated
 in greater detail in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Two-Sided-Lattice"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the left-shift operator, then the analog of the transfer operator can
 be roughly taken to be the right-shift operator.
 Since the lattice is one-sided, there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 inequivalent right-shift operators 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{k}(\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)=(k,\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)\label{eq:Lattice right-shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These right-shift operators are inverses to the left shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 only on one side, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\circ S_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the identity, but 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}\circ\tau$
\end_inset

 is not.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 has no left-inverse, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 throws away data in its action.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 case, the shift operators act on the Cantor mapping as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x(S_{0}(\sigma))= & \frac{x(\sigma)}{2}\\
x(S_{1}(\sigma))= & \frac{1+x(\sigma)}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so one may immediately recognize how to pose the Bernoulli operator
 on the lattice model.
 For some arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Omega\to F$
\end_inset

 one defines 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}f\right](\sigma)=\frac{1}{2}\left[f(S_{0}(\sigma))+f(S_{1}(\sigma))\right]
\]

\end_inset

For the general 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic case, this generalizes trivially:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic Bernoulli operator acting on the space of functionals of lattice configura
tions is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{p}f\right](\sigma)=\frac{1}{p}\sum_{k=0}^{p-1}f\left(S_{k}(\sigma)\right)\label{eq:Lattice Bernoulli}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th right-shift operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{p}$
\end_inset

 on the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{p}H=\mathcal{L}_{p}V+\lambda H\label{eq:Lattice shift eigenfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is easily shown by direct substitution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critical result here is that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{p}V=0$
\end_inset

.
 Curiously, this implies that functions in the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 can be used to construct eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The above construction is not limited the the Bernoulli operator, but clearly
 is a general result: it is essentially the Wold decomposition of section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Wold-decomposition"

\end_inset

, but restated in a a more general form: rather than requiring a Hilbert
 space, it holds for arbitrary Cartesian products over arbitrary spaces,
 provided only that the summation in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lattice Hamlitonian"

\end_inset

 is convergent (and/or meets any other criteria for the space being worked).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may construct a large number of general eigenfunctions, provided that
 on can find non-trivial objects in the kernel, and provided that one is
 working in a topology where the sum of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lattice Hamlitonian"

\end_inset

 converges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fractal eigenfunctions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Fractal-eigenfunctions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above derivation of the eigenfunctions assumed a lattice model (Cartesian
 product) topology for the unit interval.
 Using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Cantor mapping"

\end_inset

 to regain the natural topology on the real numbers, one may use the constructio
n to rediscover the full set of eigenfunctions of the Bernoulli operator.
 This is done explicitly in this section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coordinate kernel"

\end_inset

, it was seen that the kernel of the Bernoulli operator consists of the
 odd harmonics of sine and cosine: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{L}_{B}\sin2\pi(2k+1)x & =0\\
\mathcal{L}_{B}\cos2\pi(2k+1)x & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a non-negative integer parametrizing the kernel; however, it will be
 more convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp2\pi i\left(2k+1\right)x$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 rang e over all integers, positive and negative.
 A simple linear combination over positive and negative 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 will regain the real form.
 Inserting these into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lattice Hamlitonian"

\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}\exp\left(2\pi\left(2k+1\right)\tau^{n}x\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is an eigenfunction: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}H=\lambda H$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp$
\end_inset

 is periodic, we may replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}x$
\end_inset

.
 Switching notation, one has a collection of eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{\lambda,k}^{B}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}\exp\left(2\pi i\;2^{n}\left(2k+1\right)x\right)\label{eq:dyadic exp fractal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 This derivation allows 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in F$
\end_inset

 for any field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

; taking 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to be the complex numbers, the sum converges absolutely for the disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

 and conditionally for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|=1$
\end_inset

, depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a root of unity or not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 denotes that these are eigenfunctions for the 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset

 case of the Bernoulli operator.
 For the general case, one builds the eigenfunctions out of the shift states
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{n,k,r}^{(p)}(x)=\exp2\pi ix\left(pk+r\right)p^{n}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remainder
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0<r<p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n,k,r}^{(p)}(x)$
\end_inset

 are shift states of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{p}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{p}v_{n,k,r}^{(p)}\right](x)=v_{n-1,k,r}^{(p)}(x)\label{eq: p-adic Shift states}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ne0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{p}v_{0,k,r}^{(p)}\right](x)=0$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This is obtained by simple substitution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{p}v_{n,k,r}^{(p)}\right](x) & = & \frac{1}{p}\sum_{m=0}^{p-1}v_{n,k,r}^{(p)}\left(\frac{x+m}{p}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{p}\exp\left[2\pi ix\left(pk+r\right)p^{n-1}\right]\sum_{m=0}^{p-1}\exp\left[2\pi i\frac{m}{p}(pk+r)p^{n}\right]\\
 & = & v_{n-1,k,r}^{(p)}(x)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The sum in the middle line above is a Gauss sum
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Apo76"

\end_inset

, and may be shown to equal 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ne0$
\end_inset

 and equal to zero otherwise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above relationship is reminiscent of of the creation and annihilation
 ladder operators of quantum mechanics.
 This correspondence can be made stronger, and is explored in a later section.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic shift states of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: p-adic Shift states"

\end_inset

 can be trivially used to construct the eigenstates of the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic Bernoulli operator.
 These are given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}\exp\left(2\pi ix\;\left(pk+r\right)p^{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

 which clearly obey 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{p}\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}=\lambda\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These eigenfunctions are highly degenerate, and span an infinite-dimensional
 space labeled by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Any linear combination of these is also an eigenvector with the same eigenvalue.
 These clearly form a continuous spectrum for the Bernoulli operator, although,
 strictly speaking, this spectrum is defined only on the unit disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 This is in contrast to the zeta eigenfunctions, which are defined for the
 entire complex 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-plane (although these are not integrable when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|>1$
\end_inset

).
 This implies that the construction of eigenfunctions by means of lattice
 shifts is somehow innately limited: it allows some, but not all possible
 eigenfunctions to be found.
 The true nature of this obstruction is unclear.
 The proximal cause of the obstruction is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}\lambda^{n}=1/(1-\lambda)$
\end_inset

 has a pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, thus preventing the convergence of the analytic series beyond that point.
 However, in the more global view, one has an operator acting on an infinite-dim
ensional topological vector space; whether the obstruction is due to the
 operator or the structure of the space itself is unclear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytic properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the zeta function eigenvectors, these eigenvectors are not infinitely
 differentiable.
 Taking the first derivative, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}(x)=2\pi i\left(pk+r\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p^{n}\lambda^{n}\exp\left(2\pi ix\;\left(pk+r\right)p^{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and so the right hand side converges absolutely only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1/p$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|>1/p$
\end_inset

, the eigenfunction is continuous but not differentiable.
 This is visualized in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fractal-Eigenfunction"

\end_inset

.
 Second derivatives may be taken only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1/p^{2}$
\end_inset

; more generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th derivatives may be taken only when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1/p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

