\begin_layout Subsection
The Fractal Spectrum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fractal spectrum can be re-expressed in terms of the zeta eigenfunctions,
 and vice-versa.
 That is, the one set of eigenfunctions can be expressed as linear combinations
 of the other.
 This section gives the explicit linear relations connecting the one to
 the other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The establishment of this result is the observation that every integer has
 a unique factorization in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $(pk+r)p^{n}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k,r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 uniquely determined when 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is fixed.
 This leads to a summation identity: for a fixed integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and some arbitrary summable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\;\sum_{r=1}^{p-1}\;\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\; f\left((pk+r)p^{m}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The summand of the triple sum on the right is precisely of the form appearing
 in the fractal eigenfunctions, whereas the left-hand side is of the simpler
 form of the zeta eigenfunctions.
 The desired linear relationship is obtained merely by matching terms in
 the series.
 That is, one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)=2\Gamma(s+1)\,(2\pi n)^{-s}\exp(2\pi ixn)$
\end_inset

 to immediately obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\beta(x;s) & = & \frac{2\Gamma(s+1)}{(2\pi)^{s}}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\;\sum_{r=1}^{p-1}\frac{1}{(pk+r)^{s}}\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{\exp2\pi ix(pk+r)p^{m}}{p^{ms}}\\
 & = & \frac{2\Gamma(s+1)}{(2\pi)^{s}}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\;\sum_{r=1}^{p-1}\frac{1}{(pk+r)^{s}}\,\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}(x)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where one identifies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=p^{-s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full set of zeta eigenfunctions, accounting for degeneracy, is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{n}(x;s)\equiv\beta(x;s+2\pi ni/\ln2)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}.$
\end_inset

 These share the same eigenvalue: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{p}\beta_{n}=p^{-s}\beta_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The relevant values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 should be restricted to a principal domain 
\begin_inset Formula $-\pi<\Im s\,\ln2=\arg\, z<\pi$
\end_inset

 .
 Repeating the above manipulations, the goal is to write the zetas as a
 linear combination of the fractal eigenfunctions, so: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{n}(x;s)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\;\sum_{r=1}^{p-1}F_{nkr}\,\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}(x)
\]

\end_inset

These matrix elements are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{nkr}=2\Gamma\left(s+1+\frac{2\pi ni}{\ln2}\right)\left(2\pi(pk+r)\right)^{-s}\exp\left[-2n\pi i\frac{\ln\pi(pk+r)}{\ln2}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Presumably 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is invertible; the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}$
\end_inset

 should be expressible in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}(x;s)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analytic situation is curious: the zeta eigenfunctions are well-defined
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|>1$
\end_inset

, even as the fractal eigenfunctions are not.
 The change-of-basis summations clearly appear to be divergent as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|$
\end_inset

 approaches 1.
 It would appear that the zeta eigenfunctions span a larger space than the
 fractal eigenfunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discontinuous eigenfunctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the eigenfunctions are not continuous in the natural topology of
 the reals.
 Thus, for example, given the expansion in binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{2^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

Then the Cantor or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Devil's staircase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{\lambda}\left(x\right)=\lambda\left(\lambda-1\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(-1\right)^{b_{n}}\lambda^{n}
\]

\end_inset

is easily shown to be an eigenfunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This function is clearly discontinuous for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 except 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1/2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\lambda}\left(x\right)=B_{1}\left(x\right)=x-1/2$
\end_inset

.
 The Devil's staircase function is shown in 
