\begin_layout Standard
This eigenfunction is not 'new', but is rather a linear combination of those
 already presented.
 To see this, generalize the construction.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\lambda,k,r}^{(p)}(x)$
\end_inset

 were built up explicitly from sine waves, but there is no particular reason
 to start with a sine-wave basis for the kernel.
 Consider, for example, the square wave or Haar wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x)=\begin{cases}
+1 & \mbox{ for }0\le x<1/2\\
-1 & \mbox{ for }1/2\le x<1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

extended to the entire real-number line as a periodic function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x+n)=h(x)$
\end_inset

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The Haar wavelet is in the kernel of the Bernoulli operator: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}h(x)=0$
\end_inset

, and thus can be used to create a fractal eigenfunction by means of the
 lattice shift equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lattice shift eigenfunction"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}h\left((2k+1)2^{n}x\right)\label{eq:Haar wavelet eigenfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}\psi_{k}=\lambda\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|<1$
\end_inset

 in the unit disk.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a special case: 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\lambda}\left(x\right)=\lambda\left(\lambda-1\right)\psi_{0}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, and so we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic exp fractal"

\end_inset

.
 By the Fourier decomposition theorem, 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 periodic function odd about 1/2 will consist entirely of odd harmonics,
 and can thus be used to define an eigenfunction in the manner of eqn
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Haar wavelet eigenfunction"

\end_inset

.
 That it is a linear combination of the basis vectors 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic exp fractal"

\end_inset

 follows trivially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a few practical reasons for choosing a basis other than the sine-wave
 basis.
 Most notably, convergence properties are altered: the Haar wavelet can
 avoid the Gibbs phenomenon of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ringing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that makes absolute bounds difficult to establish.
 The Haar wavelet also seems more compatible with the product topology of
 the lattice; it has a particularly simple form when considered as a function
 on the lattice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note, incidentally, that even more 'horrible' eigenfunctions can be constructed
 in this fashion.
 Consider, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(x-\frac{1}{4}\right)-\delta\left(x-\frac{3}{4}\right)$
\end_inset

, extended to be periodic on the real line.
 It may be expressed as a Fourier series; it lies in the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 It may be used to create a fractal eigenfunction: integrable but not square-int
egrable and certainly not bounded, thus showing that there are eigenfunctions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 that are in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 but not in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 This foreshadows some of the more challenging functions one encounters
 when analyzing other transfer operators, such as the GKW operator
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-GKW"

\end_inset

.
 It also vindicates the focus on measurable functions on the product topology:
 the Dirac delta function is far easier to 'understand' as a measure on
 a topology than as a Fourier series.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fractal Symmetry and the Dyadic Monoid
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
------------xxxxxxxxxxxx------------xxxxxxxx
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fractal eigenfunctions are self-similar.
 This self-similarity follows directly from the shift invariance of the
 lattice construction, that is, of the translation invariance of the lattice
 Hamiltonian embodied in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Hamiltonian left shift"

\end_inset

.
 Loosely speaking, one might say that translation-invariant Hamiltonians
 must necessarily have fractal eigenfunctions.
 The self-similarities have a non-trivial structure, which is exposed in
 this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For concreteness, consider first the action of the right-sift operators
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, defined by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lattice right-shift"

\end_inset

, acting on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 dyadic eigenfunction 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Haar wavelet eigenfunction"

\end_inset

 built from the Haar wavelet.
 One has (dropping the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 from
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[S_{0}\cdot\psi\right](x) & = & \psi\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}h\left(2^{n-1}x\right)\\
 & = & h\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\lambda^{n-1}h\left(2^{n-1}x\right)\\
 & = & h\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda\psi(x)\\
 & = & -1+\lambda\psi(x)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with the last step following because the Haar wavelet is identically -1
 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<1/2$
\end_inset

.
 To emphasize this, write it more simply as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=-1+\lambda\psi(x)
\]

\end_inset

That is, one very explicitly has that the eigenfunction on the whole unit
 interval looks exactly like the eigenfunction on the half-interval, except
 that its scaled and offset: this is classic fractal self-similarity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the other shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, one readily obtains that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}\psi=1+\lambda\psi$
\end_inset

.
 The action of these two shift operators has a representation in terms of
 2x2 matrices acting on two-dimensional vectors.
 The basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1}$
\end_inset

 for this vector space are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1\mapsto e_{0}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\psi\mapsto e_{1}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{0}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1\\
0 & \lambda
\end{array}\right]\quad\mbox{ and }\quad S_{1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
0 & \lambda
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:Dyadic generators}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that one has, for example 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}e_{1}=-e_{0}+\lambda e_{1}$
\end_inset

 as the action of the right shift on this vector space.
 The two matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 generate a monoid, the 
\emph on
dyadic monoid
\emph default
.
 A general element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the monoid is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=S_{0}^{n_{0}}S_{1}^{n_{1}}S_{0}^{n_{2}}S_{1}^{n_{3}}\cdots
\]

\end_inset

for non-negative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0},n_{1},n_{2},\cdots$
\end_inset

 .
 The monoid is free, in that there are no relations between 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, and each unique string of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{0},n_{1},n_{2},\cdots$
\end_inset

 results in a unique element of the monoid.
 For the purpose of this text, a 
\emph on
monoid
\emph default
 is defined much as a group, except that inverses are not considered.
 This is for two reasons: first, the inverses of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 are not uniquely defined: the left and right inverse differ.
 Secondly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is to be understood to be the action of a monoid element acting on the
 unit interval.
 As long as the action maps the whole interval into a sub-interval, the
 action is well-defined; however, there are technical difficulties with
 going in the reverse direction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dyadic monoid has many interesting properties; these are discussed in
 greater detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-T04"

\end_inset

.
 Among the notable properties is that the dyadic monoid is isomorphic to
 a certain subset of the Modular Group; this connection alone being important
 as the modular group plays an important role in number theory, specifically
 in the area of modular forms and automorphic forms.
 Not inconsequential is that the theory of modular forms again borders on
 the theory of the Riemann zeta.
 In a similar vein, one notes that the string of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $[n_{0},n_{1},n_{2},\cdots]$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to a continued fraction.
 Continued fractions are important both to the theory of Diophantine equations
 (Pellian equations), and in turn are seen to tie back into general phenomena
 seen in ergodic dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integral of the Haar wavelet or square wave is the tent map or triangle
 wave
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t(x)=\int_{0}^{x}h(y)\, dy=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{1}{2}-2x & \;\textrm{ when }\; & 0\leq x\leq1/2\\
-\frac{3}{2}+2x & \;\textrm{ when }\; & 1/2\leq x\leq1
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

This is extended to the entire real line by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $t(x+n)=t(x)$
\end_inset

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The triangle wave has the curious property of period-doubling upon iteration:
 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{k}(x)=-t(2^{k-1}x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>1$
\end_inset

.
 The iterated tent map behaves as a shift state, in that the Bernoulli operator
 acts as an annihilation operator: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}t^{k}\right](x)=t^{k-1}(x)
\]

\end_inset

with the shift terminating at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}t\right](x)=0
\]

\end_inset

The fractal eigenfunction constructed from the triangle wave is the Takagi
 or blancmange curve: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{\lambda}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}t(2^{n}x)
\]

\end_inset

and so of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}b_{\lambda}=\lambda b_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 There is a curious special case: the Takagi curve 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1/4}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a parabola, corresponding to the Bernoulli polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Apparently, the construction of the parabola by self-similar subdivision
 was known to Archimedes
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Man88"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The blancmange curve transforms under a three-dimensional representation
 as the Haar-wavelet curve, in that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}b_{\lambda}=-\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right)+\lambda b_{\lambda}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad S_{1}b_{\lambda}=\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right)+\lambda b_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

Taking as the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1\mapsto e_{0} & = & \left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
x\mapsto e_{1} & = & \left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]\\
b_{\lambda}\mapsto e_{2} & = & \left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

the two generators may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & \frac{1}{2}\\
0 & \frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}\\
0 & 0 & \lambda
\end{array}\right]\quad\mbox{ and }\quad S_{1}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \frac{1}{2} & -\frac{1}{2}\\
0 & \frac{1}{2} & \frac{1}{2}\\
0 & 0 & \lambda
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This process can be extended arbitrarily.
 One may choose to integrate the triangle wave, or to make a more general
 ansatz.
 Given some arbitrary polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

, one may fashion a piece-wise polynomial periodic wave 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
-p(x) & \;\textrm{ when }\; & 0\leq x<1/2\\
p\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \;\textrm{ when }\; & 1/2\leq x<1
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x+1/2)=-q(x)$
\end_inset

 or equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}q\right](x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 From this, one constructs the fractal wave 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\lambda}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}q(2^{n}x)
\]

\end_inset

which transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}f_{\lambda}=-p\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda f_{\lambda}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad S_{1}f_{\lambda}=p\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda f_{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

If the degree of the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then the associated linear representation is 
\begin_inset Formula $m+2$
\end_inset

 dimensional.
 One may choose as the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}=x^{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\le m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{m+1}=f_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 are obtained by expanding the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x/2)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the chosen basis.
 There is nothing special about the monomial basis; one might consider any
 basis where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}$
\end_inset

 represents a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As should be clear from the above construction, when 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)$
\end_inset

 is not a polynomial, the representation cannot be finite-dimensional.
 In particular, the sine-wave based dyadic fractal 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic exp fractal"

\end_inset

 constructed from 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=\exp2\pi ix$
\end_inset

 does not transform under a finite-dimensional representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general dyadic case 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ne0$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\lambda,k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}q\left(2^{n}\left(2k+1\right)x\right)
\]

\end_inset

does not change the situation.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{B}q\right](x)=0$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x+1/2)=-q(x)$
\end_inset

, and so again, the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}f_{\lambda,k}=q\left((2k+1)\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda f_{\lambda,k}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad S_{1}f_{\lambda,k}=-q\left((2k+1)\frac{x}{2}\right)+\lambda f_{\lambda,k}
\]

\end_inset

As before, if 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)$
\end_inset

 is made from a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, the resulting fractal function transforms under an 
\begin_inset Formula $m+2$
\end_inset

 dimensional linear representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic case proceeds in a similar manner.
 Polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

