\begin_layout Standard
The shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be understood to be an operator that pops a bit off the right-hand
 half lattice, and pushes it onto the left half-lattice.
 In the dyadic notation, it can be recognized as the so-called 
\emph on
Baker's map
\emph default
, a map from the unit square onto itself that cuts the square into two pieces,
 and stacks and squashes them.
 That is, given a pair of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 in the unit square, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau(x,y)=\left(\frac{x+\left\lfloor 2y\right\rfloor }{2}\,,\,2y-\left\lfloor 2y\right\rfloor \right)
\]

\end_inset

The Baker's map can be studied in its own right as a discrete-time dynamical
 system, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 can be taken to define the time evolution of a unit square over a single
 time-step.
 The time evolution is invertible, in that the inverse map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined, being 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau^{-1}(x,y)=\left(2x-\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor \,,\,\frac{y+\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor }{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The inverse map can be seen to be identical to the forward map with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 interchanged: that is, translation to the left on the lattice is identical
 to translation to the right, with left and right exchanged.
 One may say the map is 
\begin_inset Formula $PT$
\end_inset

-symmetric, with 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 standing for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parity exchange
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leftrightarrow y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time inversion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\leftrightarrow\tau^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-sided lattice may be studied either as a lattice model, or as a
 dynamical system with time evolution given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 It is interesting to juxtapose these two viewpoints.
 As a lattice model, one is typically only interested in lattices for which
 the energy and the probability density are invariant under the action of
 the translation operator.
 That is, one is interested only in the classical Hamiltonians of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Classical Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 which are translation-invariant: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\left(\tau^{n}\sigma\right)=H\left(\sigma\right)
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considered as a dynamical system, one is typically interested in the time
 evolution of densities on the unit square, that is, of real-valued maps
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:[0,1]\times[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The time evolution of a density can be simply understood as a physical
 model, where the density is a local density of some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of points 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

, with the time evolution of each point given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the time evolution of this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or density is given by the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{T}\rho\right](x,y)=\left(\rho\circ\tau^{-1}\right)(x,y)=\rho\left(2x-\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor \,,\,\frac{y+\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor }{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The transfer operator is thus a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is the set of functions on the unit square.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator.
 Here, the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is used to remind us that this is now the transfer operator on the two-sided
 lattice; it can be written as a combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{B}$
\end_inset

 and the Koopman operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{B}$
\end_inset

 for the single-sided lattice.
 One is interested in characterizing the eigenfunctions and eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general idea behind equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Classical Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 can be immediately appealed to, to construct some of the eigenstates of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, on considers functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\lambda^{n}g\circ\tau^{n}\label{eq:Baker's eigenstates}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

given some function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 and number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Formally, such an 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an eigenstate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}f=\lambda f$
\end_inset

.
 In practical terms, it is evident that not all possible 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can make the sum convergent, although one might expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 on the unit circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|=1$
\end_inset

 of the complex plane might lead to a convergent sum.
 Thus immediately, one deduces that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 must surely be a unitary operator.
 The unitarity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 makes intuitive sense in a certain way: the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is invertible, and one expects time-reversible evolution to be described
 by unitary operators.
 The figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:Ising-Tartan"

\end_inset

 shows a tartan-like distribution corresponding to 
