\begin_layout Section
\start_of_appendix
Review of Dirac Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This appendix reviews the Dirac or bra-ket notation on the polynomial and
 square-integrable spaces, and illustrates this by performing a calculation
 that mixes the two.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-Polynomial-Representation"

\end_inset

, we constructed the polynomial space, and its dual.
 In Dirac notation, the basis vectors are the monomials: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle x|n\right\rangle =x^{n}
\]

\end_inset

 while the dual vectors are the linear functionals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle n|x\right\rangle =\frac{(-1)^{n}}{n!}\delta^{(n)}(x)
\]

\end_inset

That these are truly dual is expressed by equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:orthogonality"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytic completeness"

\end_inset

; namely, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle n|m\right\rangle =\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}_{A}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left|n\right\rangle \left\langle n\right|$
\end_inset

.
 The later may be understood as the identity operator on the space of polynomial
s, or, more broadly, on the space of analytic functions.
 This interpretation is justified by realizing that it is just a formalized
 notation for the Taylor's series in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Taylors bra-kets"

\end_inset

.
 The monomials, and their duals, truly provide a basis for the space of
 analytic functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now review the analogous situation, this time for the Hilbert space
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 of square-integrable functions.
 The review is remedial but is needed to present the surprising results.
 One writes, for some (periodic) function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, the Fourier Series as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=a_{0}+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\cos2\pi nx\;+b_{n}\sin2\pi nx
\]

\end_inset

where the conjugates of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=2\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\,\cos(2\pi nx)\, dx
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{n}=2\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\,\sin(2\pi nx)\, dx
\]

\end_inset

The sine and cosine notation is somewhat awkward, and it will be easier
 to use the complex exponential 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(i2\pi mx\right)=\cos\left(i2\pi mx\right)+i\sin\left(i2\pi mx\right)$
\end_inset

.
 At the same time, let us move over to bra-ket notation.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|em\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 will denote the basis vectors for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 These may be defined in terms of their components in coordinate space,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x|em\right\rangle =\exp(i2\pi mx)$
\end_inset

.
 The conjugate vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle en\right|$
\end_inset

 have an equally simple representation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle en|x\right\rangle =\exp(-i2\pi nx)$
\end_inset

.
 These are orthogonal over coordinate space in the usual sense: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle em|en\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{1}dx\,\left\langle em|x\right\rangle \left\langle x|en\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{1}dx\,\exp(2\pi i(n-m)x)=\delta_{nm}
\]

\end_inset

These are also complete over coordinate space, in that, for any arbitrary
 square-integrable coordinate-space function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\left\langle x|f\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 , one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\left(x\right)= & \int_{0}^{1}dy\,\delta(x-y)\, f(y)\\
= & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\exp(i2\pi nx)\int_{0}^{1}dy\,\exp(-i2\pi ny)f(y)\\
= & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\exp(i2\pi nx)\int_{0}^{1}dy\,\left\langle en|y\right\rangle \left\langle y|f\right\rangle \\
= & \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\left\langle x|en\right\rangle \left\langle en|f\right\rangle \\
= & \left\langle x\right|\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\left|en\right\rangle \left\langle en\right|\left|f\right\rangle \\
= & \left\langle x\right|1_{F}\left|f\right\rangle \\
= & \left\langle x|f\right\rangle 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The above made use of the usual expansion of the Dirac delta as a Fourier
 series:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\left(x-y\right)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\exp\left(i2\pi n\left(x-y\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

The completeness of the basis over 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 may be expressed as a decomposition of the identity operator on 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{F}=\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\left|em\right\rangle \left\langle em\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Here, the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 reminds us of the Fourier-series nature of this identity operator.
 The identity operator has the matrix elements that one expects in both
 the Fourier space and in coordinate space: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle em\right|1_{F}\left|en\right\rangle =\delta_{nm}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x\right|1_{F}\left|y\right\rangle =\delta(x-y)$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, all of the above definitions and developments are standard textbook
 fare.
 We now embark on a slightly more challenging calculation: to show that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle m\right|1_{F}\left|n\right\rangle =\delta_{nm}$
\end_inset

.
 In the process, one encounters some divergent sums; these can, however,
 be rescued by means of analytic continuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Begin by writing the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|em\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 in the polynomial-space representation.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ne0$
\end_inset

, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle n|em\right\rangle = & \int_{0}^{1}dx\left\langle n|x\right\rangle \left\langle x|em\right\rangle \\
= & \int_{0}^{1}dx\,\frac{(-1)^{n}}{n!}\delta^{(n)}(x)\, e^{i2\pi mx}\\
= & \int_{0}^{1}dx\,\frac{\delta(x)}{n!}\,\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\, e^{i2\pi mx}\\
= & \frac{(i2\pi m)^{n}}{n!}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle n|e0\right\rangle =\delta_{n0}$
\end_inset

.
 Essentially, this is nothing more than a plain-old Taylor's series expansion
 of the exponential function; reasonable, insofar as the exponential function
 is an entire function on the complex plane.
 The first step in the above was to insert the coordinate-space identity
 operator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1_{C}=\int_{0}^{1}dx\left|x\right\rangle \left\langle x\right|
\]

\end_inset

That 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{C}$
\end_inset

 deserves the status of an identity operator may be seen by noting that,
 for any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(y\right)=\left\langle y|f\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{1}dx\left\langle y|x\right\rangle \left\langle x|f\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{1}dx\delta\left(y-x\right)f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

, where we made use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle y|x\right\rangle =\delta\left(y-x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conjugate vectors have a slightly trickier form.
 They are the Fourier components of monomials.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ne0$
\end_inset

 one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle em|n\right\rangle = & \int_{0}^{1}dy\left\langle em|y\right\rangle \left\langle y|n\right\rangle \\
= & \int_{0}^{1}\exp(-2\pi imy)\, y^{n}\, dy\\
= & \frac{-1}{2\pi im}+\frac{n}{2\pi im}\int_{0}^{1}\exp(-2\pi imy)\, y^{n-1}\, dy\\
= & -\frac{1}{2\pi im}\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\frac{n!}{(n-k)!}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi im}\right)^{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

while, for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

, one simply has 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle e0|n\right\rangle =1/(n+1)$
\end_inset

, and, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle em|0\right\rangle =\delta_{m0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now try to explicitly evaluate the matrix elements of the Fourier
 identity operator 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{F}$
\end_inset

 in the polynomial representation.
 That is, we attempt to write the matrix elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{F}=\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\left|em\right\rangle \left\langle em\right|$
\end_inset

.
 So, by direct substitution,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle p\right|1_{F}\left|n\right\rangle = & \sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\left\langle p|em\right\rangle \left\langle em|n\right\rangle \\
= & \sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\left[\delta_{p0}+\left(1-\delta_{p0}\right)\frac{\left(2\pi im\right)^{p}}{p!}\right]\left[\frac{\delta_{m0}}{n+1}-\frac{\left(1-\delta_{m0}\right)}{2\pi im}\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\frac{n!}{(n-k)!}\left(\frac{1}{2\pi im}\right)^{k}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Consider first the matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\ne0$
\end_inset

, to see the misery of this expression: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle p\ne0\right|1_{F}\left|n=1\right\rangle =-\frac{\left(2\pi i\right)^{p-1}}{p!}\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[m^{p-1}-\left(-m\right)^{p-1}\right]
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 even, the sum on the right vanishes.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 even, the sum on the right is formally divergent.
 One may rescue the situation by making the Ansatz that the summation should
 have been replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(1-p)$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 that the summation should be replaced by it's analytic continuation, which
 is the Riemann zeta function.
 So:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle p\ne0\right|1_{F}\left|n=1\right\rangle =-\frac{2\left(2\pi i\right)^{p-1}}{p!}\zeta\left(1-p\right)
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1,$
\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(0\right)=-1/2$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p=1\right|1_{F}\left|n=1\right\rangle =1$
\end_inset

 as expected.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 odd, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(-2k\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

, and so one has exactly what was expected: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p\ne0\right|1_{F}\left|n=1\right\rangle =\delta_{p1}$
\end_inset

.
 Calculations for other values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are somewhat more difficult, but ultimately provide the expected answer:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle p\right|1_{F}\left|n\right\rangle =\left\langle p|n\right\rangle =\delta_{pn}$
\end_inset

.
 There is, however, a cautionary tale that becomes clear as one tries to
 carry out this calculation: the manipulations can become painful, and formally
 divergent sums are best avoided before-hand, by re-arranging terms before
 they become a problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Koopman Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Koopman operator is in a certain sense conjugate to the Frobenius-Perron
 operator, and defines how observables evolve.
 Given a density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 we say that the observation of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle f\,\right\rangle _{\rho}=\int_{0}^{1}f(x)\rho(x)\, dx
\]

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

observable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from usage in quantum mechanics, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is associated with the eigenvalues of an operator.
 We do not need to appeal to these operator equations for the following
 development.
 The Koopman operator 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 gives the change in 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 acts on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, thus: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{g}:\left\langle f\,\right\rangle _{\rho}\rightarrow\left\langle K_{g}f\,\right\rangle _{\rho}=\int_{0}^{1}[K_{g}f](x)\rho(x)\, dx=\int_{0}^{1}f(x)[U_{g}\rho](x)\, dx
\]

\end_inset

In Dirac bra-ket notation, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}f(x)[U_{g}\rho](x)\, dx= & \int_{0}^{1}\left\langle x|U_{g}|\rho\right\rangle \left\langle x|f\right\rangle \, dx\\
= & \int_{0}^{1}dx\int_{0}^{1}dy\left\langle x|U_{g}|y\right\rangle \left\langle y|\rho\right\rangle \left\langle x|f\right\rangle \, dx
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[K_{g}f\right](y)=\int_{0}^{1}\left\langle x|U_{g}|y\right\rangle \left\langle x|f\right\rangle \, dx=\int_{0}^{1}U_{g}(x,y)f(x)\, dx=\int_{0}^{1}\delta\left(x-g(y)\right)f(x)\, dx
\]

\end_inset

This gives the action of the Koopman operator in a coordinate-space representati
on.
 As is the recurring theme, different representations can lead to different
 results.
 In the coordinate-space representation, the Koopman operator appears to
 be the transpose of the Frobenius-Perron operator, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x,y)=U(y,x)$
\end_inset

.
 However, in a general representation, whether the Koopman operator is the
 transpose or the complex conjugate or something else needs to be determined
 on a case-by-case basis, with an appeal to the particular operator 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 and the representations on which it works.
 
\end_layout

